---
<SiteLayout site="28grams" title="Sourdough Feeding Schedule: Ratios, Timing, and Fridge Storage" description="Master your sourdough starter feeding schedule with this comprehensive guide covering ratios, timing, temperature effects, and long-term fridge storage." canonical="https://28grams.vip/sourdough-feeding-schedule" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Sourdough Feeding Schedule</h1>
      <p>Mastering ratios, timing, temperature effects, and long-term fridge storage to keep your starter thriving on your own timeline.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>The Importance of a Feeding Schedule</h2>
      <p>A sourdough starter is a living culture of wild yeast and lactic acid bacteria. Just like any living organism, it requires a consistent food source to survive and thrive. The food, in this case, is fresh flour and water. How often you provide this food, and in what quantities, dictates not only the health and vigor of your starter but also the flavor profile of the bread it produces. If you haven't yet created your starter, head back to our foundational <a href="/sourdough-starter-guide">Sourdough Starter Guide</a> to get began.</p>

      <p>The core mechanism of feeding is dilution. As your starter ferments, it consumes the starches in the flour, produces carbon dioxide (causing the rise), and generates acids (lactic and acetic acid). Over time, the environment becomes highly acidic and depleted of nutrients. By discarding a portion of the old starter and introducing fresh flour and water, you are diluting the acidity and replenishing the food supply, allowing the yeast and bacteria populations to multiply anew.</p>
      <p>Understanding how to manipulate your feeding schedule is the key to making sourdough baking fit seamlessly into your life, whether you are a daily baker or a weekend warrior. The three main variables you can control are the feeding ratio, the frequency of feeding, and the temperature of the environment.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Understanding Feeding Ratios</h2>
      <p>When bakers talk about feeding ratios, they are referring to the proportion of starter to fresh flour to fresh water, almost exclusively measured by weight in grams. The standard notation is Starter:Flour:Water. These ratios are crucial because they determine how large of a 'meal' you are providing to your yeast population.</p>

      <h3>The Standard Maintenance Ratio: 1:1:1</h3>
      <p>This is the baseline ratio for most bakers. It involves equal parts by weight of starter, flour, and water. For example, you might retain 50g of mature starter, and feed it with 50g of flour and 50g of water. This ratio provides a moderate meal. At a typical room temperature of 70-74°F, a 1:1:1 fed starter will usually reach its peak activity in about 4 to 6 hours.</p>

      <h3>The Slow-Down Ratio: 1:2:2 or 1:3:3</h3>
      <p>If you need your starter to peak later—perhaps you want to feed it before bed and mix your dough in the morning—you need to provide a larger meal. By increasing the ratio of fresh food to starter, you dilute the initial yeast population more significantly, meaning it will take them longer to consume the food and reach peak activity. A 1:2:2 feed (e.g., 25g starter, 50g flour, 50g water) or a 1:3:3 feed (e.g., 20g starter, 60g flour, 60g water) are excellent for an overnight build, typically peaking in 8-12 hours depending on the ambient temperature.</p>

      <h3>The Vacation Ratio: 1:5:5 or higher</h3>
      <p>Sometimes you need to slow things down dramatically, perhaps to revive a neglected starter or to prepare it for an extended stay on the counter without a feed. A very high ratio like 1:5:5 (e.g., 10g starter, 50g flour, 50g water) provides a massive buffet for a small population of yeast. This can take 12-24 hours to peak at room temperature. High ratios are also known to dilute the acidity significantly, which can lead to a milder, less sour flavor profile in your final bread. If you are struggling with a starter that smells excessively vinegary, a few high-ratio feeds can help rebalance it. For more on resolving these issues, consult our <a href="/sourdough-troubleshooting">Sourdough Troubleshooting Guide</a>.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>The Role of Temperature</h2>
      <p>Temperature is the invisible ingredient in sourdough baking. It acts as the accelerator or the brake pedal for fermentation. The wild yeast and lactic acid bacteria in your starter are most active in a warm environment and sluggish in a cold one.</p>

      <h3>Room Temperature (70°F - 75°F)</h3>
      <p>This is the ideal temperature range for maintaining an active starter that you plan to use frequently. At these temperatures, the yeast reproduces steadily, and the bacteria produce a balanced mix of lactic and acetic acids. If your kitchen runs cold, especially in the winter, your starter will take longer to peak, regardless of the ratio you use. You might need to find a warmer microclimate, such as above the refrigerator or in an oven with just the interior light turned on.</p>

      <h3>Warm Environments (76°F - 85°F)</h3>
      <p>In warmer environments, fermentation happens rapidly. A 1:1:1 feed might peak in just 3 hours. If you live in a hot climate, you may find that you need to feed your starter multiple times a day to prevent it from exhausting its food supply and becoming overly acidic, or you will need to switch to higher feeding ratios (like 1:3:3) for your standard maintenance feeds.</p>

      <h3>Cold Storage (The Refrigerator)</h3>
      <p>The refrigerator (typically around 38°F) slows fermentation to a crawl. This is the ultimate tool for bakers who cannot commit to daily feedings. Storing your starter in the fridge allows you to manage it on your own schedule, effectively putting the yeast to sleep until you need them again.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>The Weekend Baker's Schedule (Fridge Storage)</h2>
      <p>For most home bakers, feeding a starter twice a day is impractical. The refrigerator method allows you to bake incredible sourdough bread with just a few minutes of active maintenance per week.</p>

      <h3>The Weekly Routine</h3>
      <p>Let's assume you want to bake a loaf of bread on Saturday morning. Here is a typical schedule:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Sunday to Thursday:</strong> Your starter lives quietly in the refrigerator, unfed.</li>
        <li><strong>Thursday Evening:</strong> Remove the starter from the fridge. It may have a layer of dark liquid (hooch) on top; this is normal. Stir it in or pour it off. Discard down to a small amount (e.g., 25g) and feed it a 1:1:1 or 1:2:2 ratio with warm water to wake it up. Leave it on the counter overnight.</li>
        <li><strong>Friday Morning:</strong> The starter should be active and bubbly. Discard and feed it again. This second feeding ensures the yeast population is fully invigorated and ready to work.</li>
        <li><strong>Friday Evening:</strong> The starter is at its peak. Use the required amount to mix your bread dough.</li>
        <li><strong>Friday Night (Putting it to bed):</strong> Take the remaining starter (you only need a small amount, perhaps 20-30g), feed it a standard 1:1:1 ratio. Let it sit at room temperature for 1 to 2 hours so the yeast can begin consuming the new food, and then place the jar back in the refrigerator until next Thursday.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>This routine ensures your starter is robust when you need it, without the waste of daily discarding. Speaking of waste, if you find yourself with too much discard while building up your starter for the weekend, remember to check out our <a href="/sourdough-discard-recipes">Sourdough Discard Recipes</a> for delicious ways to use it up!</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Conclusion</h2>
      <p>There is no single "correct" feeding schedule for a sourdough starter. The best schedule is the one that fits your lifestyle, your baking frequency, and the environmental conditions of your kitchen. By understanding how ratios dilute the yeast population and how temperature controls the speed of fermentation, you hold the power to dictate when your starter is ready to bake.</p>
      <p>Don't be afraid to experiment. If your starter is peaking too quickly while you are at work, increase the feeding ratio or use slightly cooler water. If you only bake twice a month, embrace the refrigerator method. The goal is to make sourdough baking an enjoyable, sustainable practice, not a chore. With these principles in mind, you can confidently manage your culture, ensuring it remains healthy, active, and ready to produce beautiful, naturally leavened bread whenever you are.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
